1. Key Concepts to Remember for SAA

The Architecture in One Sentence
Global access does not require global storage.

Transit Gateway — SAA High Frequency Topic
TGW is REGIONAL - one TGW per region
Cross-region = TGW Peering Attachment between two TGWs
TGW peering uses AWS private backbone - never public internet
Each VPC attaches to its LOCAL TGW only
TGW is transitive - A can reach C through B
VPC Peering is NOT transitive - A-B and B-C does not allow A-C
Use TGW when: many VPCs, compliance requirements, need centralized routing control
Use VPC Peering when: simple 2-VPC connection, lowest cost

Networking Rules
NAT Gateway must be in a PUBLIC subnet - exam trap
Route tables attach to SUBNETS not VPCs
Public subnet = route to IGW. Private subnet = route to NAT
Security Groups are STATEFUL - return traffic auto-allowed
NACLs are STATELESS - must allow both directions explicitly
SG rules reference CIDRs across VPCs - not SG IDs from other VPCs

RDS Rules
Always in private subnets - publicly_accessible = false
Requires DB Subnet Group spanning at least 2 AZs
storage_encrypted = true for APPI and HIPAA compliance
Security Group should allow only specific CIDRs - never 0.0.0.0/0

